03841nam a22005295i 9780226620862DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082006ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802266208627 a10.7208/97802266208622doi  a(DE-B1597)524470  a(OCoLC)695288888  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQ127.E8bO45 2006 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a508.09409031222  aNU 15002rvk1 aOgilvie, Brian W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Science of Describing :bNatural History in Renaissance Europe /cBrian W. Ogilvie. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2008] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (431 p.) :b14 halftones, 21 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tConventions -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The World of Renaissance Natural History -- t3. The Humanist Invention of Natural History -- t4. A Science of Describing -- t5. Common Sense, Classification, and the Catalogue of Nature -- t6. Conclusion: What Was “Renaissance Natural History”? -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOut of the diverse traditions of medical humanism, classical philology, and natural philosophy, Renaissance naturalists created a new science devoted to discovering and describing plants and animals. Drawing on published natural histories, manuscript correspondence, garden plans, travelogues, watercolors, and drawings, The Science of Describing reconstructs the evolution of this discipline of description through four generations of naturalists. In the late fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries, naturalists focused on understanding ancient and medieval descriptions of the natural world, but by the mid-sixteenth century naturalists turned toward distinguishing and cataloguing new plant and animal species. To do so, they developed new techniques of observing and recording, created botanical gardens and herbaria, and exchanged correspondence and specimens within an international community. By the early seventeenth century, naturalists began the daunting task of sorting through the wealth of information they had accumulated, putting a new emphasis on taxonomy and classification. Illustrated with woodcuts, engravings, and photographs, The Science of Describing is the first broad interpretation of Renaissance natural history in more than a generation and will appeal widely to an interdisciplinary audience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aNatural historyzEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aSciencezEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aScience, Renaissance. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226620862423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226620862.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles